{"id":"mai-b955","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 2: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 2: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian\n\n## 1. Instructor Framing Assessment\n\nThe framing is mostly pointing at the right place, but it has one important bias: it assumes the fix should probably stay CRDT-shaped. Primary evidence says the corruption is not an Obsidian-only bug and not mainly an fsnotify bug. It is a snapshot-merge bug caused by rebuilding fake CRDT peers from an **ancient base (`creationBody`) on every sync**.\n\nSo the better framing is:\n\n- **General problem:** maitake is trying to merge external full-file snapshots as if they were native CRDT peers.\n- **Obsidian's role:** Obsidian just triggers the bug often because it autosaves frequently and writes whole-file snapshots.\n- **Main failure mode:** repeated syncs replay already-synced text as fresh concurrent inserts, so duplicates accumulate.\n\nA second bias: the current tests make the system look safer than it is. Some tests only check that a marker string is present, not that the final body is correct or stable.\n\n## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)\n\nAfter reading `pkg/crdt/crdt.go`, `pkg/crdt/diff.go`, `pkg/notes/docs.go`, `cmd/mai/daemon.go`, `pkg/crdt/yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs`, and the listed tests, my initial hypotheses were:\n\n1. `mergeViaCRDT()` is using the wrong merge base. The code fetches the creation note body and uses that as the 3-way base every time.\n2. Frequent full-file saves from Obsidian amplify the issue because every save replays the whole document delta from that stale base.\n3. The daemon is probably not the root cause. It may amplify frequency, but the corruption should be reproducible with direct `SyncDocs()` calls.\n4. `lastSyncBody()` being empty is likely a smoking gun.\n5. Even if CRDT stays, the file-side peer should start from the **last synced CRDT state**, not from a freshly rebuilt document created from old plain text.\n\n## 3. Research Path — every avenue explored\n\n### Source read completely\n\nMandatory files read fully:\n\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff.go`\n- `pkg/notes/docs.go`\n- `cmd/mai/daemon.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_fsnotify_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_test.go`\n- `test/docs_adversarial_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs`\n\nAlso read supporting code relevant to state persistence and write paths:\n\n- `pkg/notes/engine.go` (`initYDoc`, `updateYDoc`, `autoSyncDoc`)\n- `pkg/notes/fold.go` (`ydoc` event folding)\n- `pkg/notes/types.go`\n- `test/integration_test.go` (`setupRepo` helper)\n- `test/obsidian_compat_test.sh`\n\n### Git history checked\n\nRan:\n\n- `git log --oneline -30 -- pkg/crdt/ pkg/notes/docs.go cmd/mai/daemon.go`\n- inspected key commits:\n  - `8ea1ad8` — initial CRDT engine\n  - `1aae181` — unique client IDs + full-state merge\n  - `4ecfad6` — diff engine\n  - `d6c9944` — CRDT 3-way merge in `SyncDocs`\n  - `9c6e6bb` — debounce delete events for atomic saves\n  - `a37b6c6` — adversarial docs tests / autoSync fix\n\n### Ticket / plan search\n\n- `mai ls` reviewed for prior research and plan tickets\n- found the Delphi epic (`mai-4z3y`) and architecture ticket (`mai-n5q3`)\n- found no completed prior `research,oracle` result tickets yet; only other oracle assignments were in progress/open\n- no separate plan ticket surfaced for this bug\n\n### Web research\n\nSearched for:\n\n- Obsidian autosave behavior / save cadence\n- Obsidian conflict handling\n- Yjs/Yrs behavior when overwriting whole content or replaying stale diffs\n- Logseq / Foam / Dendron style sync approaches\n\nKey outside findings:\n\n- Obsidian community/plugin threads repeatedly describe autosave on a short debounce (~2s) and full-file saves.\n- fsnotify issue history confirms that many editors do atomic save patterns (`Remove` + `Create` / rename), which matches why `9c6e6bb` exists.\n- Obsidian Sync uses **3-way text merge via `diff-match-patch` for markdown**, not CRDT, and even exposes a conflict-file option when auto-merge is undesirable.\n- Yjs guidance consistently assumes peers exchange Yjs updates / manipulate Yjs shared types directly. A Yjs community answer on duplicate content points to the classic failure mode: treating a whole new document snapshot as a concurrent overwrite causes duplication.\n- Logseq markdown mode and Foam workflows are file/git/sync-tool based, not CRDT-at-file-boundary designs.\n\n### Local experiments\n\n#### Experiment A — reproduce corruption without daemon\n\nI wrote a small repro program against the public Go APIs. Sequence:\n\n1. create doc note with body:\n   ```\n   alpha\n   beta\n   gamma\n   ```\n2. materialize to `docs/guide.md`\n3. simulate full-file save to add `delta`\n4. sync\n5. simulate full-file save to add `epsilon`\n6. sync\n7. simulate full-file save changing `beta` -\u003e `BETA`\n8. sync\n\nObserved output:\n\n```text\nSTEP 1 len=23\nalpha\nbeta\ngamma\ndelta\n\nSTEP 2 len=37\nalpha\nbeta\ngamma\ndelta\nepsilon\ndelta\n\nSTEP 3 len=51\nalpha\nBETA\ngamma\ndelta\nepsilon\ndelta\ndelta\nepsilon\n```\n\nThis reproduces the bug **without fsnotify and without Obsidian running**. That rules the daemon out as the root cause.\n\n#### Experiment B — compare `creationBody` base vs `lastSyncBody` base\n\nI ran the same logical merge using:\n\n- current behavior: `base = creationBody`\n- corrected snapshot behavior: `base = last synced body`\n\nResults:\n\n```text\nstep2 creation-base=\"alpha\\nbeta\\ngamma\\ndelta\\nepsilon\\ndelta\\n\"\nstep2 lastsync-base=\"alpha\\nbeta\\ngamma\\ndelta\\nepsilon\\n\"\nstep3 creation-base=\"alpha\\nBETA\\ngamma\\ndelta\\nepsilon\\ndelta\\nepsilon\\ndelta\\n\"\nstep3 lastsync-base=\"alpha\\nBETA\\ngamma\\ndelta\\nepsilon\\n\"\n```\n\nSo the stale base is enough to explain the duplication.\n\n#### Experiment C — existing test is too weak\n\nRan:\n\n- `nix-shell -p go --run 'go test ./test -count=1 -run TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged -v'`\n\nThe test passes, but when I reproduced its scenario directly, the actual merged body was:\n\n```text\n\"Note editFile edit.\\n\"\n```\n\nThe test only checks that `state.Body` contains `\"File edit\"`, so it passes even though the result is neither exact-file-wins nor a clean merge.\n\n## 4. Dead Ends and why\n\n### Dead end: blaming unique client IDs / old CRDT merge bug\n\n`1aae181` fixed a real CRDT issue: identical client IDs across WASM instances and a broken diff/apply path for concurrent edits. That was worth checking, but it is **not** the current duplication root cause. My repro above uses the current code and still duplicates content.\n\n### Dead end: blaming fsnotify / atomic saves as the primary cause\n\n`9c6e6bb` fixed a real delete/create watcher problem. Important, but separate. The corruption happens with direct `SyncDocs()` calls and no watcher.\n\n### Dead end: assuming current tests cover the corruption\n\nThey don't. Several tests assert `Contains(...)` for markers rather than exact merged output or stability across repeated syncs.\n\n### Dead end: `lastSyncBody()` already helping\n\nIt does nothing today. It returns `\"\"` and is not used in `mergeViaCRDT()`.\n\n## 5. Key Discoveries with evidence\n\n### A. The current merge path is rebuilding fake peers from the creation body\n\nIn `pkg/notes/docs.go`, `mergeViaCRDT()` does this:\n\n- load `state.YDocState`\n- get `noteContent`\n- set `base := creationBody` (fallback to `noteContent` only if empty)\n- create fresh `baseDoc`\n- build `notePeer = base + diff(base -\u003e noteContent)`\n- build `filePeer = base + diff(base -\u003e fileContent)`\n- merge full state\n\nThat means every sync replays **all note-side history since creation** and **all file-side history since creation** as if they were fresh concurrent edits.\n\n### B. `lastSyncBody()` exists as the right idea, but is stubbed out\n\n`pkg/notes/docs.go` has:\n\n- comment explaining exactly the needed concept: “body content as it was when last synced to disk”\n- implementation: `return \"\"`\n\nSo the code already contains the missing design hint.\n\n### C. The daemon runs whole-repo docs sync on every debounced file save\n\n`cmd/mai/daemon.go` debounces writes/creates and then calls `syncFile()` -\u003e `notes.SyncDocs(...)` for the repo. With an editor that autosaves frequently, the bad merge runs frequently.\n\n### D. The bug is general to full-file-save editors, not Obsidian specifically\n\nObsidian is just a strong trigger because it autosaves often. Any editor that writes a full new snapshot to disk after each pause/save would drive the same bug.\n\n### E. The code is mixing two different models\n\n- **Real CRDT model:** peers share history / updates / state vectors\n- **Current filesystem model:** peer state is reconstructed from plain text snapshots after the fact\n\nThat mismatch is the architectural fault line.\n\n### F. `SyncDocs()` currently writes two YDoc updates for one merged body change\n\nWhen `SyncDocs()` appends a `body` event, `engine.Append(...)` already triggers `updateYDoc(...)` in `pkg/notes/engine.go`. After that, `SyncDocs()` may append another `ydoc` event from `mergeViaCRDT()`.\n\nSo one sync can emit:\n\n1. body event\n2. ydoc event produced by `updateYDoc`\n3. another ydoc event produced by `mergeViaCRDT`\n\nThat is redundant at best and obscures which YDoc state is authoritative.\n\n### G. Other tools solving similar problems do not use CRDT at the markdown file boundary\n\n- **Obsidian Sync:** 3-way text merge for markdown using `diff-match-patch`, conflict-file fallback available.\n- **Logseq markdown mode:** plain files with Git / Syncthing style sync; conflicts are handled at file/sync-tool level.\n- **Foam / Dendron ecosystems:** git/file conflict workflows, not CRDT merge from disk snapshots.\n\n## 6. Contradicting Evidence\n\nImportant counter-evidence that prevents overclaiming:\n\n1. **One-shot merges can look fine.** If there has only been one divergence from creation, the current algorithm may appear correct.\n2. **The daemon fixes are real.** The atomic-save tombstone bug was real and separate.\n3. **CRDT itself is not “broken.”** The local `pkg/crdt` wrapper can converge when peers truly share state correctly.\n4. **Using a recent sync base dramatically improves behavior.** My local comparison showed that using last-sync base content stops the duplication in the repeated-save repro.\n5. **Automatic text merge can still duplicate/garble edge cases.** Even Obsidian Sync documents that auto-merging markdown can sometimes duplicate text or formatting, which is why conflict-file mode exists.\n\nSo the answer is not “CRDT always impossible here.” The answer is: **the current way maitake feeds the file system into CRDT is wrong, and a plain snapshot-based merge fits this boundary better.**\n\n## 7. Synthesis — my answer\n\n### Bottom line\n\n**Do not use the current CRDT reconstruction strategy as the merge engine for markdown files saved by Obsidian.** The correct design is:\n\n1. track the **last synced plain-text snapshot** for each doc\n2. treat note body and file body as two descendants of that snapshot\n3. run a **real 3-way text merge** at the filesystem boundary\n4. only update YDoc state *after* the final merged body is chosen\n\n### Recommended design (best payoff)\n\n#### A. Replace `mergeViaCRDT()` in `SyncDocs()` with snapshot-based 3-way text merge\n\nMaintain per-doc sync metadata:\n\n- `last_synced_body` (exact markdown body written/read at last successful sync)\n- optionally `last_synced_hash`, `last_synced_path`, `last_synced_at`\n\nSync logic becomes:\n\n| Case | Condition | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| In sync | `note == file` | no-op |\n| Note changed only | `file == base \u0026\u0026 note != base` | write note to file; update sync base |\n| File changed only | `note == base \u0026\u0026 file != base` | append note body = file; update sync base |\n| Both changed | `note != base \u0026\u0026 file != base` | 3-way merge `(base, note, file)` |\n\nFor the merge itself, use a text merge algorithm made for file snapshots, not CRDT. `diff-match-patch` is the clearest precedent because Obsidian Sync already uses it for markdown.\n\n#### B. On overlapping/confusing conflicts, prefer explicit conflict handling over blind auto-merge\n\nFor non-overlapping paragraph/line changes, auto-merge.\n\nFor overlapping hunks, do one of these:\n\n- produce a conflict file (`*.mai-conflict.md` / `*.sync-conflict-...md` style), or\n- leave the original file and attach a conflict note/comment for manual resolution.\n\nThat is safer than silently concatenating garbage.\n\n#### C. Keep YDoc only as derived state, not as the file merge authority\n\nIf maitake wants YDoc for future native collaborative editing, fine. But for the Obsidian/file boundary:\n\n- final authority should be the merged plain text body\n- YDoc should be updated from that final body once\n- `SyncDocs()` should not append its own extra `ydoc` event after `engine.Append(body)` already updated it\n\n### Minimum-change alternative (if the team insists on CRDT here)\n\nIf CRDT must stay in the merge path, the minimum correct version is:\n\n1. persist **last synced YDoc state** and **last synced plain-text body**\n2. on file change, load current note doc from current `YDocState`\n3. load file peer from **last synced YDoc state** (shared history intact)\n4. apply `diff(lastSyncedBody, fileContent)` to that file peer\n5. merge file peer into current note doc\n6. persist merged body + new YDoc + new last-synced snapshot\n\nWhat must never happen again:\n\n- rebuilding peers from `creationBody` for ongoing syncs\n- reconstructing both sides from raw text while pretending they still share true CRDT history\n\nThis alternative is more complex and lower-payoff than plain 3-way text merge.\n\n### Why I recommend the plain 3-way merge path\n\nBecause the file boundary is fundamentally snapshot-based. Obsidian does not send Yjs operations. maitake is already reverse-engineering operations from text diffs. Once you're at that boundary, a tracked snapshot + 3-way text merge is the right abstraction.\n\n## 8. Confidence \u0026 Caveats\n\n### Confidence\n\n- **High confidence** that the current root cause is the stale `creationBody` merge base.\n- **High confidence** that the corruption is reproducible without the daemon and therefore not primarily a watcher bug.\n- **High confidence** that tests are currently too weak to prevent this regression.\n- **Medium-high confidence** that a stored last-sync snapshot + 3-way text merge is the right design for Obsidian/file sync.\n- **Medium confidence** on exact Obsidian save mechanics on every platform/version. The safe design should not depend on whether save is write-in-place, temp-file rename, or another full-snapshot pattern.\n\n### Caveats\n\n- `lastSyncBody` alone is enough to stop the reproduced duplication in the current CRDT reconstruction model, but if CRDT remains in the design I still prefer storing the last synced YDoc state too.\n- Any automatic text merge can still create ugly output on overlapping edits. A conflict-file escape hatch is worth having.\n- If the team wants future native multi-peer collaborative editing, that is a different path from syncing plain markdown files with Obsidian.\n\n## 9. Divergent Possibilities\n\n### Option 1 — Recommended\n\n**Remove CRDT from the docs-sync merge path.**\n\n- store last synced body snapshot\n- 3-way text merge for markdown\n- conflict-file fallback for overlapping hunks\n- update YDoc only after the merged body is chosen\n\nBest match to the real boundary, smallest future bug surface.\n\n### Option 2 — Transitional patch\n\n**Keep current shape, but fix the base immediately.**\n\n- implement and use `lastSyncBody()`\n- stop using `creationBody` for ongoing merges\n- add a regression test for repeated full-file saves\n- remove duplicate `ydoc` appends in `SyncDocs()`\n\nThis likely fixes the immediate bug fast, but it still leaves CRDT doing a job that text 3-way merge handles more naturally.\n\n### Option 3 — Full CRDT purist route\n\n**Persist last synced YDoc state and last synced body, and merge file changes into that true shared state.**\n\nThis is the most CRDT-consistent option, but I would only do it if maitake is committed to a future where the editor side also speaks Yjs/Yrs natively.\n\n---\n\n# Concrete test strategy I would implement\n\n## Unit tests\n\n### Pure merge tests\n\nAdd a merge helper that takes `(base, note, file)` and returns either:\n\n- merged text, or\n- explicit conflict result\n\nTest exact outputs, not `Contains(...)`.\n\nCases:\n\n1. base == note, file changed only\n2. base == file, note changed only\n3. both changed, non-overlapping paragraphs\n4. both changed, same line / overlapping range\n5. repeated full-file saves after prior syncs (the current regression)\n6. unicode / emoji / multi-byte text\n7. large markdown with headings/lists/frontmatter-separated body\n8. idempotence: merge same inputs twice -\u003e same result\n9. stability: after sync sets new base, a second sync with no changes is a no-op\n\n### Regression test for the real bug\n\nA test roughly like:\n\n- create note body `A`\n- disk save to `A1`\n- sync\n- disk full-save to `A2`\n- sync\n- disk full-save to `A3`\n- sync\n- assert final body is exactly `A3`\n- assert no duplicated lines / no growth beyond expected\n\nName suggestion:\n\n- `TestSyncDocs_RepeatedFullFileSaves_DoNotDuplicateContent`\n\n## Integration tests\n\n1. `SyncDocs()` without daemon, full-file rewrite each time\n2. daemon-driven save loop with debounce\n3. atomic save pattern: remove/create or temp-file rename\n4. `rm -rf docs/` then restore, then edit again\n5. Obsidian-style append/edit sequence against a 2k-10k word markdown file\n\n## Adversarial tests\n\n1. concurrent note edit + file edit on different paragraphs\n2. concurrent note edit + file edit on same paragraph\n3. rapid repeated saves with no semantic change\n4. large document with repeated autosaves every few hundred ms\n5. verify no corruption after N sync cycles (not just one)\n\n## Property/invariant tests\n\nFor generated text triples `(base, note, file)`:\n\n- if `note == base`, result must equal `file`\n- if `file == base`, result must equal `note`\n- if `note == file`, result must equal that exact text\n- syncing twice without new edits must not change the body\n- merged body should not grow on repeated identical inputs\n\n## Test repairs needed in current suite\n\n- strengthen `TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged` to assert exact expected behavior\n- add exact-body assertions where current tests only check substring presence\n- unskip fsnotify tests once watcher behavior is deterministic enough to trust\n\nThat is my answer.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:18:07Z","branch":"main"}
